ral art: The example of the frescoes at Domitilla catacomb/Rome -- tThe Rhetoric of Violence and Healing in the Church of Prophites Elias in Thessaloniki -- tThe Wondrous World of the Cinema: Types of Depictions of the Miraculous in Jesus Films -- tV Rethinking the Miraculous -- tMiracles Revisited. A Short Theological and Historical Survey -- tNew Testament Healing Narratives and the Category of Numinous Power -- tThe Concept of Miracle and the Concepts of Reality. Some Provisional Remarks -- tMarvels, Miracles, Signs and the Real: Peirce’s Semiotics in Religion and Art -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex of Subjects and Persons -- tIndex of Biblical Sources -- tIndex of Authors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince David Hume, the interpretation of miracle stories has been dominated in the West by the binary distinction of fact vs. fiction. The form-critical method added another restriction to the interpretation of miracles by neglecting the context of its macrotexts. Last but not least the hermeneutics of demythologizing was interested in the self-understanding of individuals and not in political perspectives.The book revisits miracle stories with regard to these dimensions: 1. It demands to connect the interpretation of Miracle Stories to concepts of reality. 2. It criticizes the restrictions of the form critical method. 3. It emphasizes the political implications of Miracle Stories and their interpretations.Even the latest research accepts this modern opposition of fact and fiction as self-evident. This book will examine critically these concepts of reality with interpretations of miracles. The book will address how concepts of reality, always complex, came to expression in stories of miraculous healings and their reception in medicine, art, literature, theology and philosophy, from classic antiquity to the Middle Ages. Only through such bygone concepts, contemporary interpretations of ancient healings can gain plausibility.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMiraclesxBiblical teaching. 0aRealityxBiblical teaching. 4aMethodik des Neuen Testaments. 4aRealitätskonzepte. 4aRezeptionsgeschichte des Neuen Testaments. 4aWunderheilung. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Criticism & Interpretation / New Testament.2bisacsh  aConcepts of Reality.  aHealing Miracles.  aNew Testament Methodology.  aReception of the New Testament.1 aAlkier, Stefan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlkier, Stefan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBetcher, Sharon V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeuser, Hermann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErwin, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahl, Werner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeppin, Hartmut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoffitt, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoel, James A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOcker, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRydryck, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchroeder, Rossitza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulz, Heiko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTieleman, Teun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWainwright, Elaine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeissenrieder, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ct